@Media:	020522, audio
@Date:	19-JUN-1972
@Tape Location:	Tape 36 , side 1
@Comment:	This is tapes 36 , 37 , and 38.
@Situation:	playing
@Comment:	Several things were new or unique in these sessions. This was Lynn's first time with Peter and although he was a bit shy early in each session , he seemed to adjust very quickly to the new person. He enjoyed playing with her. The doll house and doll furniture were new to Peter. On the first day , he was quite overwhelmed at the beginning of the session , merely dumping the toy furniture in the house. Later that day and the next day , he tried other ways to play with the house , including getting in it himself. Peter had just returned from two weeks with his grandmother and teen aged uncle in Philadelphia. Peter's mother commented on the disappearance of "right" and the substitute use of "yeah." She also feared he had learned some four letter words from his uncle , but none appeared in his speech during the sessions. Mother felt that it had sometimes been difficult for the family in Philadelphia to understand Peter. She based that partly on the fact that Peter frequently uses "what? what? what?" when somebody else said something and Mother believed it must have been said to him often. Her response has been to wait without repeating herself , or to repeat only once , and it is clear that "what?" like "hm: (rising intonation) " rarely meant "I didn't hear you" although it sometimes meant "I don't understand you."
@Comment:	Lois and Patsy noticed a striking change in Peter's response to questions. He answered questions such as what did you open? (the door); what are you doing? (trying) who's that (girl) where should I put this (over there) where's the TV? (outside) , even a "why" question: why (did you run over my blocks)? (because this is a fire engine). Many questions were unanswered , or not answered comprehensibly , of course. He answered most yes/no questions with yeah or no , sometimes giving a more complete response. He asked many "wh" questions , including questions in which it was not clear whether the "wh" from was meant to be where , who , or what. He also attempted to ask some questions too complicated for him , using other forms to fill those functions , eg: "who's that" for "who is that" and almost every who and what question he could think of for "who are you." (He finally gave up on that one) Another very noticeable change was the appearance of many incorrect inflections and variation of forms: who breaked it , now he knocks , what's that noising , this falled out , ect.
@Types:	long, toyplay, TD
